The OSI model is 7 layers.The OSI model is 7 layers. From the bottom (Layer 1) up to the top (Layer 7):
7 — Application — the layer users and programs actually interact with; where protocols like HTTP, FTP, SMTP, DNS, and DHCP live.
6 — Presentation — translation, formatting, encryption/decryption, and compression (TLS/SSL, JPEG, ASCII). Think of it as making sure data is in a usable, readable form.
5 — Session — establishes, manages, and ends the connection (session) between two devices.
4 — Transport — end-to-end delivery using TCP and UDP; this is where ports live, plus reliability and flow control.
3 — Network — logical addressing and routing; IP addresses and routers operate here.
2 — Data Link — physical addressing with MAC addresses; switches operate here, and it uses Ethernet/ARP.
1 — Physical — the actual hardware and signals: cables, hubs, NICs, and the raw bits on the wire.
The standard memory trick, bottom to top (Physical → Application): "Please Do Not Throw Sausage Pizza Away." Some people go top to bottom instead with "All People Seem To Need Data Processing"

APFS snapshots are a feature of APFS (Apple File System) — the file system
Apple uses on modern Macs, iPhones, and iPads. A snapshot is a read-only,
point-in-time image of the file system: it captures exactly what every file
looked like at the instant the snapshot was taken, and freezes that state so
you can return to it later.
